        "body": "The chapter opens mid-defense. Paul has been explaining (since 1:15) why he changed his travel plans — he had promised a double visit (Corinth → Macedonia → Corinth again) and instead went only to Troas and Macedonia. His critics in Corinth had seized on this as evidence of apostolic vacillation, a yes-and-no leader (1:17-18). Paul's answer here is precise: he changed plans *for their sake*, to spare them another *painful* visit (*lupe*, 2:1). The first visit had already been painful; another one — with the offender unrepentant — would have produced sorrow Paul refused to inflict.\n\nThe logic of 2:2 is dense but recoverable: *if I grieve you, who will gladden me?* Paul's joy is so bound up with the Corinthians' joy (cf. 1:24 — *fellow workers of your joy*) that grieving them would destroy his own gladness. He cannot extract joy from the very people he has wounded. The pastoral economics here are anti-instrumental — Paul refuses to use sorrow to compel compliance, because the sorrow would corrode the relationship that is the only source of his own joy. Hendricks called this \"the principle of mutual stake\": real pastors cannot prosper by making their people suffer.\n\nVerse 4 is the chapter's most autobiographically raw statement. The *tearful letter* (now lost, or — less likely — identified with 1 Corinthians; most scholars including Harris and Garland take it as a separate, non-extant correspondence between 1 and 2 Corinthians) was written *out of much affliction and anguish of heart, with many tears*. The Greek piles emotional vocabulary: *thlipsis* (pressure, the same word Paul used of mortal danger in 1:4-8), *sunoche* (constriction, anguish — used elsewhere in the NT only at Luke 21:25 of cosmic distress), *kardia* (heart). And the purpose was *not* to cause sorrow but to make known *the love I have especially for you* (*perissoteros* — superabundantly).\n\nThis verse settles a perennial pastoral question: can love grieve those it loves? Paul's answer is unambiguous — *only* love grieves rightly. The tearful letter was not a failure of *agape* but its instrument. Manipulative grief uses sorrow to extract behavior; apostolic grief uses sorrow to communicate love. The two look identical from outside; they differ entirely in motive and effect. The Corinthians had received the letter and (Titus had reported, 7:6-13) repented — proving the love by responding to it.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Lupē* (sorrow, vv. 1, 3, 7) and *lupeō* (grieve, vv. 2, 4, 5) frame the chapter's emotional vocabulary. *Thlipsis* (affliction, v. 4) is Paul's signature suffering-word in this letter (used eight times — 1:4-8; 2:4; 4:17; 6:4; 7:4; 8:2, 13). *Sunochē* (anguish) appears only here in Paul and once in Luke (21:25); the cognate verb *sunechō* means to *constrict* or *hem in*. The verbal architecture is one of contained, deliberate pain — not emotional spillage but pastorally precise grief."
