        "number": 2,
        "title": "Forgive and comfort him — restoration as anti-satanic act",
        "range": "2:5-11",
        "excerpt": "Sufficient for such a one is this punishment which was inflicted by the majority, so that on the contrary you should rather forgive and comfort him… so that no advantage would be taken of us by Satan, for we are not ignorant of his schemes.",
        "body": "Paul now turns from his own grief to the offender's case. The identification of the offender has divided commentators: the older view (going back to Chrysostom) saw him as the incestuous man of 1 Corinthians 5; the modern consensus (Murray Harris, *2 Corinthians* NIGTC; Paul Barnett, *2 Corinthians* NICNT; David Garland, *2 Corinthians* NAC) identifies him as a Corinthian who publicly insulted Paul during the painful visit (cf. 7:12 — *the one who did the wrong*). The exegetical weight favors the modern view: 2:5's *he has caused sorrow not to me, but in some degree to all of you* fits a public ecclesial insult better than sexual sin, and Paul's restraint (*in some degree, in order not to say too much*) is the tact of an apostle whose own honor was at stake.\n\nThe pivot of the section is *tounantion* in 2:7 — *on the contrary*. The church has done what was required: the *majority* (*hoi pleiones*) enacted discipline that has now reached its sufficient measure (*hikanon*, 2:6 — the same root word that will reappear at 2:16 and 3:5-6 in the question of apostolic adequacy). Paul's intervention here is calibrated: he neither overrules the discipline nor extends it. He pronounces it *sufficient* and demands the contrary movement — forgiveness and comfort. The verb *parakaleo* (comfort, 2:7) is the chapter 1 keyword (used ten times in 1:3-7) now applied to the offender. The same God of all comfort who consoled the Corinthians in their grief must now comfort the man through the Corinthians.\n\nThe warning in 2:7 is severe: *otherwise such a one might be overwhelmed by excessive sorrow*. The verb *katapino* — *swallowed up* — is used in 1 Peter 5:8 of the devil seeking to *devour* believers, and Paul uses it elsewhere of death itself being swallowed up in victory (1 Corinthians 15:54). A repentant believer left in unrelieved discipline is in mortal spiritual danger. Severity that fails to release the truly repentant is not righteousness; it is destruction. Spurgeon: \"If we crush the bruised reed, the Lord will demand it of our hands.\"\n\nVerse 8's *kuroo* (reaffirm, ratify) is a legal verb — used in Galatians 3:15 of ratifying a covenant. Paul does not ask the Corinthians to *feel* love privately; he asks them to *enact* love publicly, with the formal weight of a ratification. Restoration is not an interior disposition but a corporate act. Verse 10 then binds Paul's forgiveness to the church's — *whom you forgive, I forgive also* — and stations the entire transaction *in the presence of Christ* (*en prosōpō Christou*, literally *in the face of Christ*). Every act of pardon happens before His face.\n\nThe theological climax is 2:11. The reason for restorative forgiveness is not merely the offender's welfare or the church's love but *that no advantage would be taken of us by Satan, for we are not ignorant of his schemes*. The verb *pleonekteō* means to *take more than one's share*, to *exploit*. Satan exploits unforgiveness. His *noemata* (designs, mental strategies) include creating wounds that the church's own severity will deepen. Paul names the spiritual reality plainly: a church that disciplines but refuses to restore has handed Satan the very weapon he needs. This single verse turns church discipline from a procedural matter into a battlefield decision. Calvin: \"To leave a man in sorrow whom God has received in grace is to do Satan's work for him.\"\n\n> **Greek note.** *Charizomai* (vv. 7, 10 ×3) is the verb of grace — to give freely as a favor; the noun-cognate *charis* will erupt at 2:14 (*thanks be*). *Kuroo* (v. 8) is the covenantal verb of ratification (cf. Galatians 3:15, 17). *Katapinō* (v. 7) — to *gulp down* — appears in 1 Peter 5:8 of Satan's devouring. *Pleonekteō* (v. 11) is the verb of *taking advantage*; *noēmata* (schemes) recurs at 3:14; 4:4; 10:5; 11:3 — Paul's keyword for the mind under hostile influence."
